    "created_at": "2015-08-03T01:57:51Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-08-03T01:57:51Z",
    "body": "From MSDN:\n\n>  When an application displays a window, its taskbar button is created by the system. When the button is in place, the taskbar sends a TaskbarButtonCreated message to the window. Its value is computed by calling RegisterWindowMessage(L(\"TaskbarButtonCreated\")). That message must be received by your application before it calls any ITaskbarList3 method.\n\nElectron has `setProgressBar`, `setOverlayIcon` APIs relies on `ITaskbarList3`, but the current implementation doesn't listen to the `TaskbarButtonCreated` window mesage, which is not following the guideline as quoted above.\n\nI think we can add a `taskbar-button-created` emit event in `NativeWindow`, and stress the `setProgressBar`, `setOverlayIcon` APIs should be called only after receiving the event like:\n\n```\nwin.on(`taskbar-button-created`, function() {\n   // ...\n   win.setProgressBar(0.5);\n})\n```\n"
